MAAs are water-soluble ampholytes of low molecular weight, which are composed of a cyclohexenone or cyclohexenimine chromophore substituted by amino acids or other moieties (
Chrapusta et al., 2017
). They have been isolated from marine bacteria, fungi, several animals and plants (
Wada et al., 2015
) and they possess photoprotective and antioxidant properties (
Rastogi et al., 2016
).

Brominated and sulphated phenols, are phenols substituted with one or more bromine and sulfate residues, respectively (
Murphy et al., 2014
). They are widely distributed among red (
Phillips and Towers, 1981
), brown (
Chung et al., 2003
), and green macroalgae (
Flodin and Whitfield, 1999
; 
Hartmann et al., 2018
), but occur also in ascidians, sponges and other animals (
Murphy et al., 2014
). Their ecological role is not yet clear but brominated and sulphated phenols may contribute in chemical defense and deterrence and play a role as a storage 
form for
more active metabolites (
Kicklighter et al., 2004
; 
Kurth et al., 2015
).

All solvents required for extraction and isolation were purchased from VWR International (
Vienna
, 
Austria
). Solvents for analytical experiments had at least pro analysis (p.a.) quality and were obtained from Merck (Darmstadt, 
Germany
). Deuterated solvents containing tetramethylsilane (TMS) as internal standard were supplied by Euriso-Top (Saint-Aubin Cedex, 
France
). Ultrapure water was produced by a Sartorius arium 
®
611 
UV
(Göttingen, 
Germany
) purification system. Sephadex LH-20 material and pre-packed cartridges for flash chromatography were purchased from Sigma (St. Louis, 
USA
) and Büchi (Flawil, 
Switzerland
), respectively.
